02:07.200 --> 02:09.230
Same thing here we have a minimum.

02:09.270 --> 02:11.150
The derivative crosses through zero.

02:11.270 --> 02:12.550
Here we have a maximum.

02:12.550 --> 02:15.350
The derivative crosses through zero here.

02:15.870 --> 02:20.150
And this is basically how we identify minima and maxima.

02:20.190 --> 02:23.150
Using calculus we start with the function.

02:23.390 --> 02:25.670
And then we compute its derivative.

02:25.990 --> 02:30.550
And then we set the derivative equal to zero and solve for x.

02:30.590 --> 02:37.630
That will tell us all of the points where the derivative is zero, and the points where the derivative

02:37.630 --> 02:41.790
is zero are the points where the function is turning around.

02:41.790 --> 02:46.030
So it's going from positive to negative, or it's going from negative to positive.

02:46.270 --> 02:51.750
And in that transition from positive to negative or from negative to positive, there is necessarily

02:51.750 --> 02:54.350
going to be a local extreme point.

02:54.350 --> 02:57.510
So a local minimum or a local maximum.

02:57.990 --> 02:58.150
Okay.

