So therefore we're going to get three solutions.

03:03.550 --> 03:05.630
And you see all three of those plotted here.

03:05.830 --> 03:08.630
So x equals zero.

03:08.670 --> 03:09.830
That's this point here.

03:09.990 --> 03:13.870
And x equals plus or minus the square root of three over two.

03:13.910 --> 03:16.350
Now, the exact answers don't really matter here.

03:16.350 --> 03:23.110
The point is that we identify the minima and maxima of the function by computing the derivative.

03:23.310 --> 03:30.230
Setting the derivative to zero, and then solving for x that gives us the minimum and the maximum.

03:30.710 --> 03:33.670
Now these points here these are called the critical points.

03:33.670 --> 03:37.630
They don't actually tell us which one is a minimum and which is a maximum.

03:37.790 --> 03:41.670
These just tell us that these are the points where the derivative is zero.

03:42.110 --> 03:45.750
So how can we distinguish between minima and maxima.

03:45.790 --> 03:47.670
That's really important for gradient descent.

03:47.670 --> 03:52.790
We need to know where is the minimum because we want to move towards the minimum.

03:52.790 --> 03:55.950
You learn more about the gradient descent algorithm very soon.

