04:00.510 --> 04:00.710
Okay.

04:00.750 --> 04:06.510
So it turns out that it's actually pretty straightforward to distinguish minimum from maximum points.

04:06.510 --> 04:12.150
And that's really by just looking at the derivative before and after the critical point.

04:12.270 --> 04:14.830
In particular the minima.

04:14.870 --> 04:15.070
Okay.

04:15.110 --> 04:16.030
So this is a repeat the.

04:16.030 --> 04:18.910
The minima and maxima have a derivative.

04:18.950 --> 04:19.750
This is df.

04:19.790 --> 04:22.350
The derivative of the function equals zero.

04:22.750 --> 04:30.670
When we look at the minimum, the minima have a negative derivative to the left and a positive derivative

04:30.670 --> 04:31.550
to the right.

04:31.710 --> 04:37.150
So we can see that in this example we have our derivative equals zero.

04:37.270 --> 04:40.950
When we look to the left the derivative is negative.

04:41.230 --> 04:44.550
And when we look to the right the derivative is positive.

04:44.670 --> 04:48.070
So that means that this is a minimum point.

04:48.870 --> 04:54.270
Conversely, when we look at the maxima we have the exactly the opposite situation.

04:54.270 --> 04:59.470
So the derivative is positive to the left and negative to the right.

04:59.470 --> 05:00.670
So here's the maximum.

05:00.670 --> 05:02.350
Here the derivative is zero.

05:02.590 --> 05:05.630
The derivative is positive before.

05:05.750 --> 05:09.470
So to the left and it is negative after so to the right.

05:09.670 --> 05:13.830
So that is how we distinguish minima from maxima.

05:13.830 --> 05:21.100
And the gradient descent algorithm takes advantage of this fact to to distinguish minima from maxima.

